{[show NW]

[showcards W:S7 E:S2 S:SQ,C6]

You are West. The bidding has been as shown.

You lead the \S7; \S3, \S2 and won by South with \SQ.

South then plays the \C6 from his hand. Which \C should you play?

When you have made your choice click NEXT. [choose-card CJ] [NEXT]

[show NESW]

[clear-commentary]

Play the \CJ.

You should not allow yourself to be misled by South winning the first trick with the \SQ. East does not hold either the \SA or the \SJ or he would have played it. South is just trying to be deceptive.

That means you need the next \S play to come from East, so you play your \CJ and let East win his \CA. You can be sure East has the \CA because South would have played the suit differently if he held the Ace.

East will win the \CA and return his \S through South's \S A Q. This allows you to set up your \S suit while you still have the \CK for an entry.}
[Play "W"]S7

