{[show NESW]

[showcards W:CQ]

You are West. The bidding has been as shown.

You lead the \CQ, East plays low and South wins the \CA.

South pulls trumps in 2 rounds. He then takes the \DK, \DQ, \DA, discarding a \H on the last one. Next he plays dummy's last \C to his \CK.

Having done all this, South now plays a low \H from his hand. What do you play?

When you have made your choice click NEXT. [choose-card HA] [NEXT]

[clear-commentary]

Play the \HA.

If you followed what South was doing you will realize that he has eliminated both the \Ds and \Cs from both his hand and dummy. If it isn't clear that he is now out of \Cs, just remember the bidding - he must have had 5 \Ss and 4 \Hs.

Suppose you play low on this \H (as South hopes you will). Dummy's \HK will take the trick, and when another \H is played you will have to win it with your now bare \HA. You will then have to play a \D or a \C, giving South a ruff and sluff.

But if you take your \HA now, then exit with your \H2, South can win the \HK but will still have to lose a \H to East.}
[Play "W"]CQ

